Choice of problem / Goal¶

I will work with the blood cell images dataset. This dataset contains around 12000 blood cell images with 4 cell types/labels: Eosinophil, Lymphocyte, Monocyte, and Neutrophil. I will attempt to use machine learning to be able to properly classify images with these 4 classes.

There is no Keras function to deliver the images to the baseline models, thus a function was written to extract the images. This subset will also be used for the fully connected model, as using the generator kept causing the computer to run out of memory (school "nuc")

In [4]:
def get_data(generator, batch_size):
    """
    Generator: Generated out of which data will be extracted
    batch_size: How large the subset of the data should be, where "2" divides the total data in 2.
    Output: Creates X, y variables respectively containing samples and labels.
    """
    # Store the data in X, y variables by iterating over the batches
    generator.reset()
    X, y = next(generator)  # Create first batch
    for i in range(int(len(generator)/batch_size)-1): # 1st batch already exists
        img, label = next(generator)
        # append new batch to old batches
        X = np.append(X, img, axis=0 )
        y = np.append(y, label, axis=0)
    print(X.shape, y.shape)
    return X, y

# A subset of the data will be used as to not overload these models
X_train, y_train = get_data(train_generator, 2)
X_test, y_test = get_data(test_generator, 2)

Baseline model¶

Fit and evaluate one or two classical (i.e. "not deep") supervised machine learning methods that are most suitable to serve as a reference to assess a baseline performance. Briefly motivate your choice(s).

Random Forest Classifier¶

Random forest is often used for classification, which is fitting for the current model (classification of blood cells). This method is based on ensemble learning, it combines multiple classifiers and creates several decision trees. It goes through these trees and decides the best based on majority voting, then it delivers the output/prediction.

Decision Tree¶

Decision Tree is a supervised machine learning technique also often used for classification. It also works with creating trees, where each node ask a yes/no about a specific feature and further splits the trees. This way it is able to find patterns and classify something based on answers from the decision tree.

In [14]:
# create a sequencial model
neural = keras.models.Sequential()

# Add input layer with the size of each image/numpy array
neural.add(keras.layers.InputLayer(input_shape=(120, 160, 3), name='Input'))
neural.add(keras.layers.Flatten())  # flatten to give to dense layer

# Use three layers initially just to get a rough estimate whether more are needed.
# Adding more layers might result in just nothing happening, suggesting they aren't necessary
neural.add(keras.layers.Dense(units=128, activation='LeakyReLU', name='Hidden_1'))
neural.add(keras.layers.Dense(units=64, activation='LeakyReLU', name='Hidden_2'))
neural.add(keras.layers.Dense(units=32, activation='LeakyReLU', name='Hidden_3'))

# Add a dropout layer to combat overfitting
neural.add(keras.layers.Dropout(0.3))

# create output layer with 4 units (4 labels) and 
# softmax activation (normalized output adquate for multiple labels) 
neural.add(keras.layers.Dense(units=4, activation='softmax', name='Output'))

# generate summary for model
neural.summary()

Observations¶

When it comes to neural networks, trial and error are often the first steps depending on the problem. Based on that output, parameters are adjusted.

Several parameters were tried with this fully connected model. To vary complexity, the number of layers was varied from 3-5 and nnits varied in multiples of 2 down from 256 to 16 but did not seem to alter the results.

Afterwards different activation functions were tested: relu, leaky relu and tanh, once again no changes in results. Despite every change, the model would not get much better then 30% accuracy. Even dropouts were performed after different layers in different combinations to see if at least the sligh overfitting at the end could be corrected but it did not change anything.

To observe whether the model is actually learning something from the available data, the model will be fitted again but the labels will be shuffled. Thus, the model will be learning the wrong labels and should perform worse then before.

After shuffling the labels randomly for the same model, the values did not seem to change much as the model still seemed to mostly be "guessing" the label (see accuracy above) and overfitting at around the same number of epochs. This strongly suggests that the model is not able to take any information from the data.

Conclusion and discussion fully connected model¶

This technique seems to be a very poor fit for this data. As was observed, giving it random labels results in the accuracy not being affected greatly. One possibility is that the data is too complex for a fully connected model and a far larger number of nodes and layers are necessary. Possibly, a different method might perform better with this data. If the current method were to be used for this data further pre-processing of the data also might be necessary.

Possible pre-processing would include better cropping the picture so only the cell of interest is included. This could for example be done by using a rgb filter to select only the most purple parts in the images. And after then getting the images all in the same size these could be given to the model. Another step that could be included would be to reduce the image quality so that less pixels are analyzed, however this might also lead to a loss of information and is not always suggested.

# Create model
celclass = keras.models.Sequential()

# Create image input layer
celclass.add(keras.layers.InputLayer(input_shape=(120, 160, 3)))

# First convolutional layer
celclass.add(keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
celclass.add(keras.layers.MaxPooling2D())
celclass.add(keras.layers.Dropout(0.2))

# Second convolutional layer
celclass.add(keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
celclass.add(keras.layers.MaxPooling2D())
celclass.add(keras.layers.Dropout(0.2))

# Third convolutional layer
celclass.add(keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
celclass.add(keras.layers.MaxPooling2D())

# Fourth convolutional layer (test)
celclass.add(keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
celclass.add(keras.layers.MaxPooling2D())

# Dense layer
celclass.add(keras.layers.Flatten())
celclass.add(keras.layers.Dense(units=64, activation='relu'))
celclass.add(keras.layers.Dropout(0.3))

# Output layer
celclass.add(keras.layers.Dense(units=4, activation='softmax'))

celclass.summary()

Observations¶

Using Adam, the model kept stagnating at loss 1.38 and it woudn't get better then random guessing (25% accuracy). Suspecting the model had become stuck in a local minima, changing to RMSprop caused the model to immediately perform very well. Additionally, using 2 dropout layers after the convolutional layers and one after the dense layer caused the model to easily make it to about 80% accuracy before starting to overfit. At the moment the model would best if employed "early stopping" at around 12 epochs with an accuracy of 80%. After this it starts to slightly overfit the data.

Trying to apply additional regularizers did not seem to further improve the model. L1L2 normalization caused de model to immediately perform poorly, whereas batch normalization caused the model severely overfit at the first 10 epochs.

Conclusion¶

The convolutional model as well as the random trees seemed to perform best with this data. Random trees would get up to 80% accuracy in certain iterations whereas the convolutional network up to 85% with slight overfit. Convolutional networks are very well versed in handling images and likely the accuracy could go up with more preprocessing.

The images all contain lots of noise in the form of erythrocytes and filtering out just the stained cell should result in far "cleaner" data. Applying a for example a treshold filter should be able to generate a binary mask to only get the desired cells. Afterwards, detecting the centroid for each cell could then help when cropping the images.

Finally, considering the available time and techniques, 80-85% accuracy for this model is still suboptimal, but decent considering the input data. Likely, both the random trees and the convolutional network could improve from extra pre-processing. As seen throughout several iterations, the convolutional network performs slighly better then the random trees and would thus be the better choice for this dataset.
